Brenda 2025-04-04 01:25 p.m.
We believe the liability imposed on the Government under 5 MSC 1 3212.1 is more encompassing than under 42 U.S.C. 1983.

1983 only imposes liablity when an act is made under "any statute, ordinance, regulation, custom, or usage, * * *" Our statute, on the other hand, simply requires an "action" by the Government that is unconstitutional. 5 MSC 1 3212.1
Brenda 2025-04-04 01:26 p.m.
So I don't think the same requirements under our Federal caselaw can translate into Mayflower with respect to this cause of action.
Brenda 2025-04-04 01:28 p.m.
But I'd be happy to amend to include a "custom," so to say, as I do currently allege that I have been run over by the MPD a total of three times.
Brenda 2025-04-04 01:28 p.m.
They think they own the streets. It's shocking, frankly.
Brenda
But I'd be happy to amend to include a "custom," so to say, as I do currently allege that I have been run over by the MPD a total of three times.
sadoimpacto 2025-04-04 01:31 p.m.
Do this
Brenda 2025-04-04 02:08 p.m.
We would like the Court to make a finding on the issue first. We would only amend if there is a detrimental legal deficiency in the complaint.

We highly advise the Court to look into Monell, which held:

"The italicized language [of 1983] plainly imposes liability on a government that, under color of some official policy, "causes" an employee to violate another's constitutional rights. At the same time, that language cannot be easily read to impose liability vicariously on governing bodies solely on the basis of the existence of an employer-employee relationship with a tortfeasor."
Monell v. Department of Soc. Svcs., 436 U.S. 658, 692 (1978) (i've omitted the citation to not flood the channel)

I briefly touched on the issue above. The justification for denying respondeat superior claims under 1983 is merely a result of the statutory language. Under 1983, an agency must have "caused," by some official policy or custom or statute, one of its employees to violate the constitutional rights of another person. We don't see the language in 5 MSC 1 3212.1. 3212.1, which makes the Government liable for "Any * * * action * * * that impedes on an individual's rights"
